# 6. Demonstration II: normal HERBAL folio

## 6.1 Regime

HERBAL vertical process diagram / recipe notation.

## 6.2 Why this folio type is needed

A normal herbal page is necessary because this document should not only demonstrate key pages. The main claim is that ordinary manuscript pages can be read as structural-functional recipe/procedure notation. A herbal folio is therefore the best place to show the parser reading a regular page where plant imagery, token structure, and process logic interact.

The selected herbal folio should ideally have:

```text
clear root/stem/leaf/flower process structure
visible carrier/output/fraction features
several tokens from established families such as ol, ot, ok, op, ar, dy, daiin, dar
minimal dependence on uncertain transcription corrections
```

Possible candidates include strong visual/process pages already discussed in the main paper, such as f16v, f40v, f44r, f52r, or another folio with clear text-image correspondence.

## 6.3 Translation format

For the selected herbal page, each line should be rendered in three layers:

```text
Original line:
[Voynich tokens]

Structural-functional token reading:
[token 1] = ...
[token 2] = ...
[token 3] = ...

Plain functional rendering:
[ordinary explanatory rendering of the procedure]
```

## 6.4 Expected demonstration value

This page should demonstrate that the parser reads ordinary herbal material, not only special key environments. The visual plant form should be treated as a vertical process diagram: root/base/residue, stem/carrier/transfer, leaves/local process branches, and flower/output or collector structures.

The purpose is to show how an initiated user could read the page as a practical compressed recipe or procedure, not merely as botanical description.

