# 7. Demonstration III: BALNEO folio — radial ASTRO single-glyph operator key

## 7.1 Regime

BALNEO flow/reservoir/process endpoint.

## 7.2 Why this folio was selected

A balneo page is necessary because BALNEO reorganizes the same operator inventory into hydraulic, reservoir, carrier, body-position, and flow logic. This shows that the parser is regime-dispatched rather than mechanically identical across all sections.

A strong candidate is f75r or a related BALNEO page where `dainy` can be demonstrated in visual context.

## 7.3 Key token example

```text
dainy
```

## 7.4 Structural split

```text
dainy = d + a + i + n + y
```

## 7.5 Structural-functional translation

```text
d = transformation / processing
a = toward / into
i = phase marker
n = phase boundary / stage endpoint
y = closure / finalization
```

Full reading:

```text
dainy = transformation toward a phase endpoint, closed/finalized
```

## 7.6 Plain functional rendering

The process is brought into a phase endpoint and finalized. In BALNEO context, this may correspond to a completed local process state, finished flow stage, or closed phase transition.

## 7.7 Visual correspondence

The visual context is read as a balneo flow/reservoir system. Under the model, the figure associated with `dainy` is not a decorative bather but a process-position marker showing a completed or endpoint state within the hydraulic/regime logic.

## 7.8 Demonstration value

This folio shows how a five-glyph token can be a complete compact instruction. It also shows why one-glyph tokens are normally absent in running text: the complete instruction requires a sequence of operators.

